    Demo Task 02 - Initial review complete (Closed / Review)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the SECOND of the 8-task demo dataset; together with
    tasks 01 and 03 through 08, it satisfies the AAP requirement
    (Section 0.7.4) of providing demo tasks that exercise the resolve-
    blocker and resolve-success gates on both case-type flows. The
    complete 8-task fixture matrix:

        Task 01 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 02 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)  ## THIS FILE
        Task 03 - Open        / Follow-up     / parent case 04 (Pending GI)
        Task 04 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 05 - Closed      / Other         / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 06 - In Progress / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 07 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 08 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-task dataset thus exercises:
      * All 4 task types - this task is one of three Review-typed
        demonstrators (the others being task 04 on case 05 and task 08
        on case 09); Review represents the agent's pre-resolution or
        intermediate validation / sign-off activity, where the case
        worker reads through the case body, confirms a milestone has
        been reached, and either advances or pauses the case lifecycle.
        Per AAP Section 0.5.7 the case_task type Choice list defines
        exactly four values - Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other -
        and Review is the second value. This task ALSO carries
        operational significance distinct from the other two Review
        tasks: where tasks 04 and 08 are FINAL pre-resolution reviews
        (paired with Resolved-status parent cases), THIS task is an
        INITIAL scope-review activity that occurred BEFORE the deeper
        investigation work tracked by sibling task 01 began. The agent
        first performed an initial review of the request to determine
        the appropriate next steps (this task), closed that review
        task, then opened the deeper investigation task (task 01,
        currently Open).
      * All 3 task statuses (Open, In Progress, Closed) - this task
        contributes the FIRST of four Closed tasks (the others are
        tasks 04, 05, and 08); the Closed status is the terminal task
        status that satisfies the validate_resolved_transition
        subflow's "all child tasks must be Closed" gate. THIS task's
        Closed status is THE LOAD-BEARING DEMONSTRATION that the
        resolve gate's GlideRecord query (status != Closed) filters
        OUT closed tasks rather than counting them - meaning this task
        does NOT contribute to the resolve-blocker count for case 03
        even though it IS a child of case 03. The resolve blocker for
        case 03 comes from sibling task 01 (Open), not from this task.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this task is the
        SECOND child of case 03 (the first being task 01); together,
        tasks 01 + 02 give case 03 EXACTLY ONE non-Closed child task
        (task 01 is Open; this task 02 is Closed). The case-03 fixture
        is the canonical demonstration that the resolve gate counts
        ONLY non-Closed tasks - if the gate naively counted all child
        tasks it would block case 03 with a count of 2; if the gate
        correctly filters by status != Closed it identifies task 01 as
        the SOLE blocker (count of 1).
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry and Complaint) - this task
        sits on a General Inquiry case (case 03). The General Inquiry
        flow's resolve-BLOCKER path is exercised by tasks 01 + 02 on
        case 03; the General Inquiry flow's resolve-SUCCESS path is
        exercised by tasks 04 + 05 on case 05. THIS task is an
        ESSENTIAL HALF of the General Inquiry resolve-blocker
        demonstration: without this Closed sibling, the resolve gate
        could be misinterpreted as "blocks if any child exists"
        rather than "blocks if any non-Closed child exists." This
        task's existence as a Closed sibling of an Open task on the
        same parent case is what proves the gate's status-filtering
        semantics.
      * Both resolve outcomes (BLOCKED via at least one non-Closed task,
        and SUCCESS via zero non-Closed tasks) - this task does NOT
        directly enable a resolve-success path, but it IS the
        canonical FILTERED-OUT task that proves the resolve gate's
        query is selective rather than total. The blocker on case 03
        is task 01 alone; this Closed task is correctly excluded.

    Lifecycle position - WHY Closed / Review / parent General Inquiry case
    In Progress is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the resolve gate's GlideRecord query
      executed inside the validate_resolved_transition subflow is:

          var gr = new GlideRecord('x_casemgmt_case_task');
          gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
          gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
          gr.query();
          if (gr.next()) {
              // BLOCK: surface the verbatim error message
              //   "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          } else {
              // ALLOW: zero non-Closed tasks - case may be Resolved
          }

      Case 03 is in In Progress status with type=General Inquiry. With
      sibling task 01 (Open) plus THIS task 02 (Closed), the query
      "case = case 03 AND status != Closed" returns ONE row (task 01
      only - this task is FILTERED OUT by the status != Closed
      qualifier). The subflow blocks any attempt to transition case 03
      to Resolved and surfaces the verbatim error "All tasks must be
      closed before resolving this case." THIS TASK IS THE CANONICAL
      DEMONSTRATION THAT THE RESOLVE GATE'S STATUS-FILTERING WORKS
      CORRECTLY. Where task 01 IS the resolve-blocker for case 03,
      THIS task PROVES the gate does not over-count - it does not
      treat all child tasks as blockers, only the non-Closed ones.

      The Review task type captures the agent's pre-action validation
      work - in this case, the INITIAL scope review the agent
      performed before deciding to launch a deeper investigation. Per
      the AAP's Section 0.5.7 Choice list for case_task type, Review
      is the second of four values (Investigation, Review, Follow-up,
      Other), positioned to capture validation activities that bracket
      either the start or the end of an investigation. The "Initial
      review complete" subject makes this lifecycle role explicit: the
      agent received the case, performed an initial review of its
      scope and severity, determined that further investigation was
      needed, marked the review task Closed, and then created the
      Investigation task (task 01) that remains Open while the deeper
      work proceeds.

      The Closed status is consistent with this completed-review
      semantic: the agent reviewed the case scope, made a decision
      (proceed with investigation), and closed the review task before
      the case progressed from Open into In Progress. The transition
      narrative is therefore: case 03 was created in Draft, was
      assigned to a group/agent (Open transition), the agent performed
      THIS initial review and closed it, the agent then launched task
      01 (Investigation) and transitioned the case to In Progress
      (where it currently sits awaiting completion of task 01).

      The -3 day due_date reflects that the initial-review task was
      due three days ago (relative to the build environment date
      2026-05-01, i.e., 2026-04-28) and was completed on or before
      that date. The -3 day offset is deliberately distant from the
      sibling task 01's -3 day due_date (also -3 days) AND from tasks
      04/05's -1 day due_date - indicating that this initial review
      occurred earlier than the closing reviews on case 05 and at the
      same canonical "task is due/completed" interval as task 01. The
      relative date pattern uses negative offsets (3 days ago) for
      completed tasks, consistent with Closed status semantics (a
      task that has been started, performed, and closed, with a
      target completion date that is now in the past). The -3 day
      window is also load-bearing for the dashboard's "My Overdue
      Tasks" report contract: although the date qualifier
      (due_date < today) is satisfied, the status qualifier
      (status != Closed) excludes this task. THIS DEMONSTRATES THAT
      THE REPORT CORRECTLY FILTERS OUT COMPLETED-BUT-PAST-DUE TASKS
      RATHER THAN INCORRECTLY FLAGGING THEM AS OVERDUE - a critical
      negative-test fixture for the My Overdue Tasks widget. By
      contrast, sibling task 01 has the SAME -3 day due_date but
      Open status, making task 01 the positive-test fixture for the
      My Overdue Tasks widget and this task the negative-test fixture
      proving the status filter excludes the closed-and-past-due
      case.

