    Key insights (per the agent prompt):
      1. THIS IS THE COMPLETED INITIAL REVIEW TASK ON CASE 03. It
         demonstrates that even when an agent has done initial work
         (review complete), other tasks can still be open
         (investigation), preventing case resolution. The lifecycle
         narrative: case received -> initial review (this task) ->
         deeper investigation (task 01, still Open) -> case will
         eventually be resolvable when task 01 is also closed.
      2. THIS TASK PROVES THE STATUS-FILTERING IN THE RESOLVE GATE.
         The validate_resolved_transition subflow does NOT just count
         tasks - it counts NON-CLOSED tasks via
         addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed'). This task's
         status=Closed excludes it from the gate's blocker list. If
         a developer accidentally implemented the gate as
         "any child blocks resolve" (without the status filter),
         this fixture would surface that bug because the gate would
         incorrectly block case 03 with a count of 2 instead of 1.
      3. THE Review TASK TYPE matches "initial review" semantics. The
         agent reviewed the request scope before deciding to launch a
         deeper investigation. Review is the second of four task
         types (Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other); it captures
         pre-action sign-off work that can occur at the start
         (initial review) or end (final review) of an investigation.
      4. THE due_date IS PAST-DATED (-3 days, 2026-04-28). This is
         consistent with status=Closed - the task was due 3 days ago
         and has been completed. The relative offset preserves the
         lifecycle semantic across importation timeframes (the
         actual stored value is the static result of today - 3 days
         evaluated at this file's generation time).
      5. THE Closed STATUS USES TITLE CASE Closed. This matches the
         choice list and is the EXACT string the resolve-gate's
         GlideRecord query compares against in the addQuery('status',
         '!=', 'Closed') clause. Any case variant ("closed",
         "CLOSED", "ClOsEd") would either fail the choice
         dictionary's value validation OR (if accepted somehow) would
         not match the exact string comparison in the gate's query,
         producing incorrect resolve behavior.
      6. NO closed_date OR completed_at FIELD ON case_task. Per AAP
         Section 0.5.7, the case_task table has only 6 fields: case,
         subject, type, status, assigned_to, due_date. There's no
         separate completion timestamp; the platform's sys_updated_on
         audit field captures when the status was last changed. This
         is a deliberate simplification of ArkCase's AcmTask domain
         model (which had separate startDate/finishDate/duration
         fields) to keep the POC scoped application minimal per the
         AAP's Minimal Change Clause.
      7. THE DETERMINISTIC sys_id (md5 hash of the subject) ensures
         idempotent re-imports. If this record is re-imported (e.g.,
         during the round-trip-verify validation gate), the platform
         will recognize the existing sys_id and apply
         action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" by updating the existing record
         in place rather than creating a duplicate. The hash input is
         the literal subject string "Demo task 02: Initial review
         complete"; the resulting hex value
         (949c29a044d9fd7468ddf410173ef684) is 32 characters as
         required by the sys_id contract.
      8. THE BUILD AGENT COMPUTES due_date DYNAMICALLY at file-
         generation time so that the relative offset (-3 days) is
         preserved across importation timeframes. The actual stored
         value (2026-04-28) is the static result of today - 3 days
         evaluated at this file's generation time (today = 2026-05-01
         per the build environment date).
      9. THE casemgmt PLACEHOLDER IS PRESERVED VERBATIM in
         sys_class_name, sys_update_name, sys_scope, sys_package,
         all reference display_values that include the scope prefix
         (assigned_to display_value), and the file path. The
         placeholder is intended for downstream substitution by the
         build pipeline at the time of PDI scope assignment - the
         substitution is global across the entire scoped application
         output (every file under servicenow-case-management-poc/).
